content: What is the origin of the phrase kyrie eleison?

chosen: The Greek word “kyrios” means Lord, and "eleison" translates to 'have mercy'. Kyrie Eleison literally means ‘Lord have mercy’. The earliest use of this term was in 3rd century Rome when it became a part of Christian liturgy.
rejected: The Kyrie Eleison (also spelled "Kyrielesen") is a Greek prayer that means “Lord, have mercy.” It was first recorded in the New Testament book of Revelation and has since become one of the most widely used Christian prayers. The exact origins of the phrase are not known for certain, but it likely comes from an early form of the Greek language.
